Theresa May's Stage
London — — The task before the newly appointed British Prime Minister Theresa May is a daunting one: to carry out the demand of British — — or more precisely, English and Welsh — — voters to "leave the EU" and manage the significant consequences that this will bring.
This challenge she faces is greater than that of any previous prime minister in recent years.
But she may have the capability to accomplish this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Angela Merkel, who has shown courage in a series of crises, all the tools needed to complete the task are in May's hands.
She is smart and resilient, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not constrained by any ideology, is very skilled at maintaining control, and operates within self-defined boundaries to ensure familiarity with the issues at hand.
May has won in most of the battles she has participated in, and shows no mercy to those who have used underhanded tactics against her.
But she has few enemies within her party and is popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination — — one that she needs to fully utilize to lead the UK's Brexit process.
The Brexit process has already begun, and there is no doubt about that.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland vote to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that a Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has repeatedly said "Brexit is Brexit," and her cabinet ministers all agree with her view.
But May has not yet provided an exact definition of Brexit.
This task is very difficult to complete.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare your meal.
You would find it hard to clearly know what you are actually going to eat.
A Northern Irish "Ulster fry" — — eggs, bacon, pork sausages, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes — — with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you may feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some people may focus mainly on preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others may be more concerned about gaining access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, Britain cannot order every dish on the menu.
The reality that the Brexit supporters often overlook is that the EU will not hand out benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win hearts or punish Britain for leaving the EU (sometimes such inflammatory rhetoric is prevalent, such as the new UK Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson's claim of "Hitler-style imperialism").
On the contrary, we Britons often forget that everyone — including the EU and all its member states — has their own political or commercial interests they vow to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the coming months will be to determine what Britain's goals should be after the difficult negotiations on its relationship with the EU (and in the trade sector, its relationship with the world) begin, based on reality.
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six themes that need to be negotiated separately), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(By the time the negotiations are completed, my 11-year-old granddaughter may already be starting university!
) We must clarify the priorities in order to prevent the negotiations from taking even longer.
The goal is certainly to strike a balance between British exports and services (especially financial services) entering other European countries and restricting the movement of EU citizens into the UK.
The more negotiators gain in one area, the greater the concessions they will need to make in other areas.
Theresa May needs to fully utilize her knowledge, skills, and political capital to ensure the合理性 of the negotiation deal.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goals, she will still find that dissatisfaction is not limited to just one part — this outcome is inevitable — but rather all of them.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing May's government: narrowing the growing social divide in Britain exposed by Brexit.
Working-class regions in northern and central England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum, and they have long been distant from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the so-called proxy of globalization — the EU.
England's major cities — especially London — may benefit greatly from globalization, but they have not received any of the benefits.
Many members of the working class have ultimately become victims of Brexit populist promises due to lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by Jeremy Corbyn.
"We will reverse globalization," they said.
"We will drive out immigrants who suppress wages and redirect hundreds of millions of pounds that were originally given to the EU into public services."
They promised that Brexit would allow Britain to relive a safer and more prosperous past.
Brexit supporters cannot truly fulfill these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, just as it cannot cut off immigration from the EU.
Any such measures would only destroy British businesses.
Even if economic downturn leads to a decline in immigration, the workers who voted for Brexit may still feel disheartened to find that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and public services remain under pressure.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has already unleashed a storm of uncontrollable populist sentiment.
Just like Donald Trump was unable to improve the situation of working-class voters in the United States, Brexit cannot possibly bring benefits to those who chose it, no matter how the situation appears.
Despite having many strengths, such challenges may still be beyond May's ability to overcome.
